  <scopecontent audience="internal" id="aspace_4f1bf2aab941e8b52a4630cd30439354">
    <head>Scope and content</head>
<p>Diaries and scrapbooks; class notes from Geneseo Normal School, the University of Rochester, and Syracuse University; a photo album, and correspondence; notes relating to her teaching in Rochester, N.Y.; files relating to extension work and the Home Bureau; W.C.T.U. files; and miscellaneous clippings and publications.  Also one manuscript volume "Poems, Maybe" by Grace Evelyn Mills. Also one folder containing correspondence (1956) relating to a "fashion" exhibit mounted by Mrs. Holton, and one ticket to a lecture by Mrs. Holton in 1933.</p>  </scopecontent>
  <prefercite audience="internal" id="aspace_1ea151e147b7d405c6b2f8d6689d6de3">
    <head>Preferred Citation</head>
<p>Gladys Reid Holton papers, #4385.   Division of Rare and Manuscript Collections, Cornell University Library.</p>  </prefercite>
  <bioghist audience="internal" id="aspace_678b414677cad0ef624724360fa328b9">
    <head>Biographical / Historical</head>
<p>Gladys Reid Holton was born June 29, 1898 in Auburn, New York. She began a teaching career in the 1920s. During the 1930s-1940s she was heavily involved in traditional household arts and crafts. Holton was curator of History of the Rochester Museum of Arts and Sciences, 1950s-1960s. She retired from the Strong Museum in 1976.</p>  </bioghist>
